    <h1>High-Protein Breakfast for Men Over 40<br /><em>(7 Options, No Cooking Required)</em></h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Breakfast is where most men over 40 lose the protein game before it starts. The typical morning meal delivers 8–12 grams. You need 30. Here's how to get there.</p>
    <p class="meta">SnapProtein · 6 min read</p>
  </div>

  <article class="article-wrap">

    <div class="quick-answer">
      <div class="qa-label">Short answer</div>
      <p>Men over 40 should hit <strong>at least 30 grams of protein at breakfast</strong> — not as a bonus, but as a non-negotiable starting point. Miss it and you're already behind on your daily target before 9am. The 7 options below all hit 30g+, most take under 3 minutes, and none require cooking skill.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      I'm 64. My breakfast hasn't changed much in two years: Greek yogurt, two eggs, done. 32 grams in 90 seconds. That consistency is the whole point — not variety, not optimization, just a reliable 30g that starts the day right every single time.
    </p>

    <p>
      Breakfast is the highest-leverage meal of the day for men over 40 — not because of some morning metabolism myth, but because <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-per-day-after-40/">hitting 120–150 grams of protein per day</a> is significantly easier when breakfast does its share. Start at 8 grams and the math becomes brutal by dinner.
    </p>

    <div class="killer-line">
      Get breakfast right and the rest of the day follows.<br />Miss it and you're playing catch-up until 8pm.
    </div>

    <h2>Why 30 Grams at Breakfast Specifically</h2>

    <p>
      The 30-gram target isn't arbitrary. After 40, muscle becomes less responsive to protein — a process called <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a>. The threshold needed to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis increases with age. Doses below 25 grams often don't clear that threshold. Doses at 30–40 grams consistently do.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is why the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/30-gram-protein-rule/">30-gram rule</a> exists — and why it applies to breakfast just as much as lunch or dinner. Three meals at 30 grams gets you to 90 grams. Add a snack and you're at 115–130. Skip the breakfast dose and no amount of dinner loading closes the gap effectively.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>The breakfast gap is real:</strong> The typical American breakfast — cereal, toast, orange juice — delivers 8–12 grams of protein. That's a 20-gram deficit before the day starts. Men trying to hit 120+ grams daily cannot afford to lose that ground at meal one.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Here's the real problem in one glance:</p>

    <div style="background:var(--charcoal); border-radius:8px; padding:1.5rem 2rem; margin:2rem 0; display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr); gap:1rem; text-align:center;">
