    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is a high-protein breakfast for men over 40?</h3>
        <p>A high-protein breakfast for men over 40 should deliver at least 30 grams of protein. The most reliable options are Greek yogurt with eggs (32g), a protein shake with hard-boiled eggs (39g), cottage cheese with eggs (35g), and smoked salmon with eggs (35g). These use leucine-rich foods that reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis in older men.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much protein should breakfast have after 40?</h3>
        <p>At least 30 grams. Due to anabolic resistance, doses below 25 grams often don't reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis in men over 40. Starting the day at 30g+ sets the tone for hitting a daily target of 120–150 grams across three to four meals.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the fastest high-protein breakfast?</h3>
        <p>A protein shake with two batch-cooked hard-boiled eggs takes about 60 seconds and delivers 39 grams. Greek yogurt with pre-boiled eggs takes 90 seconds and delivers 32 grams. Batch-cooking a dozen eggs on Sunday eliminates the main time barrier for the entire week.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is breakfast so important for protein after 40?</h3>
        <p>Missing a 30g dose at breakfast means you need 120+ grams from three meals instead of four. Research consistently shows that distributing protein across four meals is more effective for muscle protein synthesis than loading it into fewer, larger meals — which is exactly what happens when breakfast is skipped or protein-poor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can you get 30 grams of protein at breakfast without cooking?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Greek yogurt with batch hard-boiled eggs, protein shakes, cottage cheese with pre-cooked eggs, and smoked salmon all hit 30+ grams with zero daily cooking. Batch-cooking eggs once a week is the only prep required — after that, most options are pure assembly.</p>
      </div>

